      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Features that decrease hERG risk**\n- **Lack of a strongly basic, readily protonated tertiary amine**: many potent hERG blockers have a cationic center at physiological pH that forms key electrostatic interactions in the pore.  \n  - The **thiazoline N\u2013H** may be only **weak-to-moderately basic** (and could be less protonated at pH 7.4 than a piperidine/tertiary amine).\n  - The **pyridine N-oxide is not a basic nitrogen** (it\u2019s zwitterionic internally, but not protonated like pyridine).\n- **Increased polarity / H-bonding** from the **tertiary alcohol** and **N-oxide** can reduce passive partitioning into the channel vestibule and may reduce effective binding compared with purely lipophilic, cationic scaffolds.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
